One suggestion about your current code
I noticed this:
customer = CustomerRepository.create(...)

WalletRepository.create_wallet(...)
Right now, your CustomerRepository.create() probably calls db.commit().
Then WalletRepository.create_wallet() also calls db.commit().
For a financial system, that's not ideal.
A better approach is:
The repositories use db.add().
The service performs one db.commit() after both the customer and wallet have been added.
That way, if wallet creation fails, the customer isn't left in the database without a wallet.
This concept is called database transactions, and it's especially important in banking and wallet applications.
What I recommend next
Don't jump into all the endpoints at once.
Build them in this order:
✅ Finish Customer CRUD
✅ Finish Wallet endpoints
✅ Build Deposit
✅ Build Withdraw
✅ Build Transfer (the hardest and most valuable one)
Once you can implement transfer correctly—with balance checks, atomic updates, transaction records, and proper error handling—you'll have built the core of a real digital wallet backend. That's the milestone I'd aim for next.